SOLVER of an HEAT PROBLEM or -div( A grad ) OPERATOR:

0: Number of INPUT DATA GAME of the operator -div A grad u + CT u
   The value 1 by default is generally correct.
   Only, the solutions of eigenvalues of a matrix polynomial and a
   not linear problem, necessitate a number of data greater 1.
   These 2 cases are programming ...

1: OBJECT NAME to treat:
   First, the NAME of the object must be given.
   This object has to be meshed and interpolated.
   If it exists only one object, Mefisto find it automatically and
   this name may be not given

2: HEAT INPUT DATA: 
   The data input for the heat problem are:
  -The MASS density, the SPECIFIC MASS HEAT, the CONDUCTIVITY,
   the DILATATION, the INTERIOR HEAT SOURCES, eventually the FLUID SPEED,
   the COEFFICIENT before the TEMPERATURE, have to be given
   at level of every component of the object: volume in 3d or surface in 2d

  -The IMPOSED TEMPERATURE (Dirichlet condition) named here CONTACT or
   the normal FLUX named here SOURCE (NEUMANN condition) or
   the heat transfer coefficient named here ECHANGE and
   the product of ECHANGE x FLUID TEMPERATURE named here SOURCE
   have to be given on every component of the boundary.

   Remark: @ permits the abandon of the data input of a component
           of the object.

   EXAMPLE :
                         L3
       P4 *----------------------------------* P3
          |                                  |
          |                                  |    
          |                                  |
          |                                  |
          |                                  |
       L4 |              S                   | L2    
          |                                  |
          |                                  |
          |                                  |
          |                                  |    
          |                                  |
          |                                  |
       P1 *----------------------------------* P2
                         L1

   HEAT CHARACTERISTICS for the STEADY problem:

   on S  : CONDUCTIVITY and internal heat SOURCE
   * means one of the 4 characters 1 or 2 or 3 or 4
   on L* : CONTACT (imposed temperature) or
           exterior SOURCE (normal heat flux, Neumann condition)
           ECHANGE and SOURCE ( ECHANGE*exterior fluid temperature)
   on P* : CONTACT if the point P* is also on one L* which
           supports exterior SOURCEs

   if L4 and L2 are subjected to exterior SOURCE and CONTACT for L3
   it is necessary to define P3 and P4 in terms of CONTACT
   in order to imposed a DIRICHLET condition (temperature)
   at these points.

   if L4 is with contact : temperature=0   degree
      L2 is with contact : temperature=100 degrees
      L3 is with a Fourier-Robin condition,
   then it is necessary to define
      P3 with CONTACT : temperature=100 degrees
      P4 with CONTACT : temperature=0   degree     
   to imposed the Dirichlet condition at these points.

   REMEMBER that at least a CONTACT at 1 point or a Fourier-Robin 
   condition IS NECESSARY to obtain a PROBLEM INVERSIBLE MATRIX!

   If the object OB is defined by : 
   surface S  line L2  line L3  line L4  point P3  point P4 
   then, by default, the exterior source (Neumann condition) on L1
   is imposed null.

3: STEADY HEAT TRANSFER solver
   The data are given. The solver can be executed.
   Choose between a direct method by Cholesky factorization
   or an iterative method by a preconditioned conjugate gradient.

4: UNSTEADY HEAT TRANSFER solver
   The data are given. The solver can be executed.
   The TIME INTEGRATION is done with an alpha scheme which is
   unconditionnaly stable if  1/2 <= alpha <= 1.
   Choose between a direct method by Cholesky factorization
   or an iterative method by a preconditioned conjugate gradient.

5: 2D WAVE solver:  rot d2 u/dt2 -div A grad u = f
   The TIME INTEGRATION is done with a NEWMARK scheme or a decentred 
   scheme which are unconditionnaly stable.

6: EIGENVALUE & VECTORS solver
   The smaller eigenvalues for the elasticity operator
   may be computed by 2 methods: SUB-SPACE or INVERSE ITERATIONS.

8: DRAWING of TEMPERATURES and FLUX
   After the computation of temperatures and fluxes,
   their drawing may be done under different forms:
   isovalues, color zones, section planes, gradient or flux arrows, ...

9: DRAWING of a WAVE
   After the computation, the vertical displacement of the wave
   may be drawn at different values of time.

10: DRAWING of PLSVO meshes
    To memorize the different meshes and recover the components
    of an object.

11: DRAWING of ISO-SURFACES f(x,y,z)=Ctes
    From a mesh of a surface and the user definition of LU function
    f(x,y,z), a drawing of isovlue surfaces f(x,y,z)=Ctes may be done.
   (A list of pseudo-temperatures at nodes is defined and the drawing
    of isovalues is done)

13: ENERGY of SOLUTIONS
    After the computation, the kinetic energy ( T [K] Tt )
    and the potential energy ( T [M] Tt ) of the temperature T
    are computed.

20: PRECISION to INVERSE A x = b
    to give the value of convergence iteration test for 
    Cholesky factorization or conjugate gradient.

